---
/* ===========================================================================
 * src/components/Subscribe.astro
 * Rhymes & Poetry — email subscribe block (sage-tinted)
 *
 * The most important conversion surface on the home page. Email is the
 * one channel YOU own — Instagram can shadowban you, Google can derank
 * you, but a list of email addresses is yours forever. For a brand
 * planning to monetize eventually, the list is the asset.
 *
 * MVP: form posts nowhere. The HTML is correct, accessibility is right,
 * client validation works — but there's no backend handler yet. Visitors
 * who hit "Subscribe" will see the browser's "form submitted" no-op.
 *
 * NEXT (when we wire it for real, possible options):
 *
 *   Option A — Buttondown (recommended for MVP)
 *     Tiny, indie-friendly newsletter service. Form action posts directly
 *     to their endpoint. No backend code on our side. ~$10/month for
 *     basic plan, free under 100 subscribers.
 *     Action URL: https://buttondown.com/api/emails/embed-subscribe/{username}
 *
 *   Option B — ConvertKit / Mailchimp / Substack
 *     Same pattern as Buttondown. Form posts to their hosted endpoint.
 *     Larger feature set, more complex setups, more expensive.
 *
 *   Option C — Self-host with Cloudflare Pages Functions
 *     POST to /api/subscribe (a Cloudflare Function), which validates,
 *     stores in a KV store or D1 database, then sends a confirmation
 *     email via Resend or SendGrid. Most control, most code to maintain.
 *
 * PUSH-RELEVANT FRAMING — this form collects PII (email addresses).
 * That triggers a real list of obligations:
 *
 *   - GDPR (EU visitors): explicit consent required, must offer
 *     unsubscribe, must allow data export and deletion.
 *   - CAN-SPAM (US): valid sender address, working unsubscribe, no
 *     deceptive subject lines.
 *   - The "no spam" promise in our copy IS legally meaningful — it's a
 *     consent statement that frames how we'll use the address.
 *   - Server-side validation is mandatory (client-side `required` and
 *     `type=email` are UX, not security — easily bypassed).
 *   - Honeypot or CAPTCHA needed to prevent spam signups via bots.
 *
 * For MVP, the form is decorative. When we wire a real handler, every
 * one of the above becomes a real engineering decision.
 * ========================================================================= */
---

<section class="subscribe" aria-labelledby="subscribe-heading">
    <div class="container">
        <h2 id="subscribe-heading" class="title">Stay close to the words.</h2>
        <p class="subtitle">
            New verses, twice a month. No spam &mdash; just words built to
            linger.
        </p>

        <form class="form" action="#" method="post">
            <label for="subscribe-email" class="visually-hidden"
                >Email address</label
            >
            <input
                id="subscribe-email"
                type="email"
                name="email"
                placeholder="your email"
                required
                autocomplete="email"
                class="input"
            />

            {
                /* Honeypot field — bots auto-fill anything labeled "name" or
          "website"; humans never see this because it's hidden. When we
          wire a real handler, reject any submission where this is filled. */
            }
            <input
                type="text"
                name="website"
                tabindex="-1"
                autocomplete="off"
                class="honeypot"
                aria-hidden="true"
            />

            <button type="submit" class="button">Subscribe</button>
        </form>
    </div>
</section>

<style>
    .subscribe {
        background: var(--rp-sage-soft);
        border-top: 1px solid var(--rp-sage-line);
        border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rp-sage-line);
    }

    .container {
        max-width: var(--rp-page-max);
        margin: 0 auto;
        padding: 64px 24px 72px;
        text-align: center;
    }

    .title {
        font-family: var(--rp-font-display);
        font-weight: 400;
        font-size: 30px;
        color: var(--rp-sage);
        margin: 0 0 10px;
        line-height: 1.2;
    }

    .subtitle {
        font-family: var(--rp-font-body);
        font-size: 16px;
        color: var(--rp-muted);
        margin: 0 0 28px;
    }

    /* ===== Form ===== */

    .form {
        display: flex;
        justify-content: center;
        gap: 8px;
        max-width: 460px;
        margin: 0 auto;
        flex-wrap: wrap;
    }

    .input {
        flex: 1;
        min-width: 220px;
        padding: 11px 14px;
        border: 1px solid var(--rp-sage);
        background: var(--rp-cream);
        color: var(--rp-ink);
        font-family: var(--rp-font-body);
        font-size: 15px;
        border-radius: 0;
        /* Sharp corners match the editorial (non-rounded) aesthetic. App-y
       inputs use radius-md, editorial uses 0. Brand-aligned details. */
    }
    .input:focus {
        outline: 2px solid var(--rp-sage-dark);
        outline-offset: 2px;
    }
    .input::placeholder {
        color: var(--rp-faint);
        font-style: italic;
    }

    .button {
        padding: 11px 22px;
        background: var(--rp-sage);
        color: var(--rp-cream);
        border: none;
        font-family: var(--rp-font-body);
        font-size: 13px;
        letter-spacing: var(--rp-track-cta);
        text-transform: uppercase;
        cursor: pointer;
        transition: background 0.15s ease;
    }
    .button:hover {
        background: var(--rp-sage-dark);
    }
    .button:focus-visible {
        outline: 2px solid var(--rp-ink);
        outline-offset: 2px;
    }

    /* Honeypot — hidden from humans (visually + from screen readers via
     aria-hidden), but bots see it and fill it. When we wire the
     backend, presence of a value in this field flags the submission
     as spam and we silently drop it. */
    .honeypot {
        position: absolute;
        left: -9999px;
        width: 1px;
        height: 1px;
        opacity: 0;
        pointer-events: none;
    }

    /* Visually hidden but available to screen readers — the standard
     accessible-but-invisible pattern for things like form labels we
     don't want to display visually but must expose semantically. */
    .visually-hidden {
        position: absolute;
        width: 1px;
        height: 1px;
        padding: 0;
        margin: -1px;
        overflow: hidden;
        clip: rect(0, 0, 0, 0);
        white-space: nowrap;
        border: 0;
    }

    /* ===== Mobile ===== */

    @media (max-width: 600px) {
        .container {
            padding: 48px 18px 56px;
        }
        .title {
            font-size: 26px;
        }
        .subtitle {
            font-size: 15px;
        }
        .form {
            flex-direction: column;
            gap: 10px;
        }
        .input {
            min-width: 0;
            width: 100%;
        }
        .button {
            width: 100%;
        }
    }
</style>
